# Electron Development Guidelines

Directives for building secure, performant Electron applications. Security first; process separation; resource management.

## Process Model

- **Main process**: Node.js environment, system APIs, window creation, IPC handlers
- **Renderer process**: Chromium-based UI; no direct Node.js access
- **IPC**: Secure typed communication between processes only

Register global handlers for `uncaughtException`, `unhandledRejection`, and `render-process-gone`; log and shut down gracefully.

## Project Structure

```
project-root/
├── src/
│   ├── main/                    # Main process
│   │   ├── index.ts             # Entry point
│   │   ├── preload.ts           # Preload script
│   │   ├── services/            # Business logic, external services
│   │   ├── handlers/            # IPC handlers
│   │   ├── windows/             # Window management
│   │   └── utils/
│   ├── renderer/                # Renderer (React)
│   │   ├── main.tsx, App.tsx
│   │   ├── components/         # ui/, features/, layout/
│   │   ├── pages/, hooks/, stores/, services/, utils/
│   └── shared/                 # Shared between processes
│       ├── types/              # TypeScript definitions
│       ├── constants/
│       └── ipc/                # IPC channel types
├── assets/, dist/, tests/, config/
```

- Co-locate related files; single responsibility per module
- Dependencies point inward toward domain logic
- Use path aliases: `@main/*`, `@renderer/*`, `@shared/*`

## Security Fundamentals

### Context Isolation and Preload

- **Always** set `nodeIntegration: false` and `contextIsolation: true`
- **Always** use a preload script; never expose `process`, `require`, or `fs` to the renderer
- Expose only the minimal API surface via `contextBridge.exposeInMainWorld`

```typescript
// Preload: validate before invoking
saveFile: (data: string) => {
  if (typeof data !== 'string' || data.length > 10000) throw new Error('Invalid data');
  return ipcRenderer.invoke('save-file', data);
}
```

### Content Security Policy

- Apply CSP to all web contents via `web-contents-created` and `onHeadersReceived`
- Restrict script sources to `'self'`; avoid `'unsafe-eval'` and `'unsafe-inline'` where possible

```typescript
'Content-Security-Policy': ["default-src 'self'; script-src 'self'; style-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline';"]
```

### Web Preferences

- Set `webSecurity: true`, `allowRunningInsecureContent: false`
- Never disable these for convenience

## IPC Communication

- Use typed channels; define `IPC_CHANNELS` or similar in `shared/ipc/`
- Validate sender: `event.sender.isMainFrame` before handling
- Validate all payloads (type, length, format) in both main and preload
- Prefer `ipcMain.handle` / `ipcRenderer.invoke` for request–response; avoid raw `send`/`on` for sensitive flows

```typescript
ipcMain.handle('save-file', async (event, data) => {
  if (!event.sender.isMainFrame) throw new Error('Unauthorised sender');
  if (typeof data !== 'string' || data.length > 1000000) throw new Error('Invalid data');
  return await saveFile(data);
});
```

## Window Management

- Centralise window creation in a dedicated module; track windows by ID
- On `closed`, remove from tracking and clean up references
- Persist bounds and maximised state to user data; restore on launch
- Ensure `webPreferences` (context isolation, preload) are applied to every window

## Resource Management and Cleanup

- Remove IPC listeners when handlers are torn down
- Dispose BrowserWindow references on close; avoid holding stale references
- Clean up timers, subscriptions, and file handles in `before-quit` or window `closed`
- Use `try/finally` or explicit dispose patterns for resources

## Performance Directives

- **Memory**: Monitor heap usage; avoid retaining large objects across window lifecycles
- **Lazy loading**: Use dynamic imports for heavy renderer modules; code-split routes
- **IPC**: Batch related operations; avoid high-frequency small messages
- **Preload**: Keep preload minimal; no heavy computation or large dependencies

## Common Anti-patterns

**Security**

- Setting `nodeIntegration: true` or `contextIsolation: false`
- Exposing `process`, `require`, `fs`, or other Node APIs in preload
- Disabling `webSecurity` or trusting remote content without validation

**Architecture**

- Mixing window, IPC, database, and security logic in one class
- Manipulating DOM from main via `executeJavaScript` with unsanitised data

**Performance**

- Failing to remove IPC or window event listeners on teardown
- Creating windows without cleanup on `closed`
- Loading all renderer code upfront instead of lazy-loading

## Checklist

### Security

- [ ] Context isolation enabled; node integration disabled
- [ ] Preload exposes minimal API via contextBridge
- [ ] CSP applied to all web contents
- [ ] All IPC messages validated (sender and payload)
- [ ] Remote content restricted; certificate errors handled

### Architecture

- [ ] Main/renderer/shared structure in place
- [ ] IPC handlers separated from business logic
- [ ] Typed IPC channels in shared layer
- [ ] Path aliases configured

### Window and Resources

- [ ] Window lifecycle managed; cleanup on close
- [ ] Event listeners removed on teardown
- [ ] Global error handlers registered

### Performance

- [ ] Lazy loading for heavy renderer modules
- [ ] Preload kept minimal
- [ ] Memory usage monitored in development
